      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/sqa-level2-criteria",
      "rationale": "The CFD solver (ANSYS Fluent 2023R2) is a commercially validated, FDA-recognized software tool. Version control, regression testing suite, and documented release notes are on file. SQA documentation meets Gradation 2 requirements for MRL 2: formal test plan executed, defect tracking maintained, and solver verification cases archived. No open critical defects affecting hemolysis-relevant flow physics."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/code-verification-level2-criteria",
      "rationale": "Code verification was performed using the method of manufactured solutions (MMS) for the incompressible Navier-Stokes solver and the scalar transport equation used for hemolysis index accumulation. Observed convergence rates matched theoretical orders (2nd-order spatial, 1st-order temporal) within 5% tolerance across three systematically refined grids. Results archived in code verification report CVR-2025-001."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/discretization-error-level2-criteria",
      "rationale": "A formal grid convergence study was conducted using three systematically refined meshes (4.2M, 11.8M, and 31.5M hexahedral elements) following ASME V&V 20 methodology. Richardson extrapolation yielded a grid convergence index (GCI) of 1.8% for the hemolysis index at the worst-case operating point (5 L/min, 3500 RPM). The fine-grid solution was adopted for all production runs. Achieved level 3 exceeds the required level 2 for MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/test-conditions-level2-criteria",
      "rationale": "Experimental bench test conditions were documented with calibrated flow meters (±1.5% FS), pressure transducers (±0.25% FS), and temperature-controlled blood analog (bovine blood, hematocrit 33±2%). Test protocols followed ASTM F1841 guidance. Boundary conditions applied in the CFD model were derived directly from measured test data with documented uncertainty propagation. Environmental conditions (temperature 37±0.5°C, pH 7.4±0.05) are consistent with physiological CPB operating range."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/output-comparison-level2-criteria",
      "rationale": "Predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) was compared against measured values across all 5 operating points. Mean absolute percentage error was 8.3% (range 4.1%–13.7%), within the acceptance threshold of 15% defined in the test plan. Relative hemolysis index RH < 1.0 was confirmed at all operating points versus the predicate device. Systematic bias was assessed via Bland-Altman analysis; no clinically significant trend was identified. Uncertainty bars from experimental measurement overlap with model predictions at all points."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/qoi-relevance-level2-criteria",
      "rationale": "The primary QoI — normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) and relative hemolysis index (RH) — directly map to the regulatory acceptance criterion (RH < 1 versus predicate). Secondary QoIs (wall shear stress distribution, exposure time histograms) are mechanistically linked to the power-law hemolysis model (Giersiepen-Wurzinger). A formal QoI traceability matrix was established linking each model output to the clinical decision (hemolysis risk classification) and the regulatory submission endpoint."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/validation-relevance-level2-criteria",
      "rationale": "Validation activities were conducted on the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump geometry under CPB-representative flow conditions (2–6 L/min, 2500–4000 RPM). The validation domain spans the intended COU operating envelope. Blood analog properties (viscosity, density) match clinical CPB conditions within documented bounds. Geometric fidelity of the validation pump to the production device is confirmed by dimensional inspection report DIR-2024-007. Extrapolation beyond the validated operating range is not required for this COU."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/solver-error-level1-criteria",
      "rationale": "Iterative convergence was monitored via residual norms for continuity, momentum, and scalar transport equations. All simulations achieved residuals below 1×10⁻⁵ for continuity and 1×10⁻⁶ for momentum before solution extraction. Mass imbalance across the domain was less than 0.01% in all cases. Round-off error was assessed as negligible given double-precision arithmetic and mesh element count. Solver error is bounded and documented in solver convergence report SCR-2025-003."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/use-error-level1-criteria",
      "rationale": "A documented simulation execution protocol (SEP-CPB-2025-001) was followed by two independent analysts. Peer review of boundary condition setup, material property assignments, and post-processing scripts was conducted and recorded. Automated input-checking scripts verified consistency between CAD geometry, mesh, and solver setup files prior to each run. Independent reproduction of the worst-case operating point by a second analyst yielded NIH values within 0.3% of the primary analyst result, confirming negligible use error contribution."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/model-form-level2-criteria",
      "rationale": "The k-ω SST turbulence model was selected based on published benchmark comparisons for rotating turbomachinery flows at similar Reynolds numbers (Re ~ 10⁴–10⁵). The Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law hemolysis model was adopted as the standard for regulatory submissions per FDA guidance. Model form uncertainty was characterized by comparing predictions from two alternative turbulence closures (k-ε realizable and Spalart-Allmaras); NIH predictions varied by less than 9% across all operating points, supporting robustness of the selected model form."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/model-inputs-level1-criteria",
      "rationale": "All model inputs (geometry, fluid properties, rotational speed, inlet/outlet boundary conditions) are traceable to calibrated measurements or published material property databases. Inlet velocity profiles were derived from measured flow rates and assumed fully developed turbulent profiles, consistent with upstream pipe lengths used in bench testing. Sensitivity of NIH to ±5% variation in blood viscosity and density was assessed; resulting NIH variation was less than 3%, confirming low sensitivity to input uncertainty at MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Test samples factor is scoped out at MRL 2 for this COU. The validation dataset uses a single representative pump geometry (FDA generic centrifugal pump) consistent with the intended production device. Sample-to-sample geometric variability assessment is not required at MRL 2 per ASME V&V 40 Table 3 guidance for Class II devices with medium model influence. Manufacturing tolerance effects on hemolysis are addressed through parametric CFD sensitivity studies documented in sensitivity report SR-2025-002, which showed NIH variation below 5% across the dimensional tolerance band."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Equivalency of input parameters is scoped out at MRL 2 for this COU. The validation experiments were conducted using the same boundary conditions (flow rate, rotational speed, fluid properties) as the simulation inputs, establishing direct correspondence without requiring formal equivalency demonstration. Any residual discrepancies in inlet turbulence intensity (experimental value estimated at 5±2% versus assumed 5%) were assessed via sensitivity study and found to produce less than 2% change in NIH, well within acceptance bounds."
    }
